{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17612385","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17612385"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:21:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:21:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16272"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16272","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16272"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0,0.68,0.04,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8963"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74615"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8963","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8963"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16272"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60109"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7021"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"},{"type":"tags","id":"10676"},{"type":"tags","id":"10677"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21331"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21335"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74615","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74615"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EFemale puberty involves complex changes in reproductive organ development that occur alongside the more visible Tanner stage changes in breast and pubic hair development.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the changes in female reproductive organs during puberty?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Decreased cervix to fundus ratio","Shortening of the uterus","Increased cervix to fundus ratio","Transition from small cystic to multicystic ovaries","No change in ovarian appearance"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring female puberty, the uterus undergoes significant morphological changes. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ecervix to fundus ratio decreases\u003C/strong\u003E as the fundus grows proportionally larger than the cervix. This is accompanied by overall uterine elongation, making \u003Cstrong\u003Eshortening of the uterus\u003C/strong\u003E incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased cervix to fundus ratio\u003C/strong\u003E would be the opposite of what occurs during normal development. The ovaries transition from a multicystic to small cystic appearance, not the reverse as suggested by the option that they \u003Cstrong\u003Etransition from small cystic to multicystic\u003C/strong\u003E. There definitely are changes in ovarian appearance, so stating there is \u003Cstrong\u003Eno change in ovarian appearance\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese changes are driven by rising oestrogen levels during puberty, which stimulate growth and development of the reproductive organs in preparation for potential future pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["During female puberty, the uterus undergoes significant morphological changes including elongation and a decrease in the cervix to fundus ratio.","The ovaries transition from a multicystic to small cystic appearance during pubertal development.","Uterine growth and development during puberty is driven by rising oestrogen levels."],"references":["Miller BS, Sarafoglou K, Addo OY. Development of Tanner Stage-Age Adjusted CDC Height Curves for Research and Clinical Applications. J Endocr Soc. 2020 Jul 17;4(9):bvaa098. doi: 10.1210/jendso/bvaa098. PMID: 32818164; PMCID: PMC7426000","Emmanuel M, Bokor BR. Tanner Stages. [Updated 2022 Dec 11]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470280/","Bridges NA, Cooke A, Healy MJ, Hindmarsh PC, Brook CG. Growth of the uterus. Arch Dis Child. 1996 Oct;75(4):330-1. doi: 10.1136/adc.75.4.330. PMID: 8984921; PMCID: PMC1511752.","Lissauer, T., \u0026 Carroll, W. (Eds.). (2021). Illustrated Textbook of Paediatrics E-Book: Illustrated Textbook of Paediatrics E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60109"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16272"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60109","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60109"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-25T22:13:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-25T22:58:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8963"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74615"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":nu